const APP_DATA = {"version": 3, "courseNotes": [{"id": "note-1", "title": "Chapter 1: License Law and Regulations", "body": "Chapter 1: License Law and Regulations\nNYS Department of State\nThe Department of State is primarily responsible for issuing real estate licenses, pocket cards, and handing down disciplinary action.\nArticle 12-A of the NYS Real Property Law outlines the roles/duties of the Department of State.\n\nAttorney General\nAccording to Article 12-A (NYS Real Property Law), the Attorney General shall prosecute criminal actions for violations of the Real Property Law.\n\nNew York Court of Appeals\nThe New York Court of Appeals is the highest court in New York State.\n\nMisdemeanor\nAccording to section 442-e of the NYS Real Property Law:\n“Any person who violates any provision of this article shall be guilty of a misdemeanor. The commission of a single act prohibited by this article shall constitute a violation hereof.”\n\nViolations of the Real Property Law\nThe Department of State may suspend or revoke a real estate salesperson or broker’s license for violations of the Real Property Law.\n\nThe DOS may also impose a fine not to exceed $1,000.\n\nReal Estate License Requirements\n\nReal estate salespersons license\nA real estate salesperson must be at least 18 years old.\nA real estate salesperson's license is valid for 2 years.\nEvery 2 years, the salesperson must renew their license online through eAccessNY.\nBefore renewing a license, the salesperson must complete 22.5-hours of Continuing Education.\n\nIf a real estate salesperson fails to renew their license within 2 years, their license is considered expired.\nThe salesperson must retake the State exam and reapply for their license.\n\nReal estate salespersons may perform acts that a broker is authorized to perform, but they do so on behalf of a broker with whom they are associated.\n\nReal estate brokers license\nOnce an individual obtains their NYS real estate salespersons license, they must do the following to obtain a brokers license:\n- Have at least two years of experience as a real estate salesperson.\n- Be at least 20 years of age.\n- Complete the 45-hour NYS real estate broker’s course (120 hours of total coursework including the 77-hour real estate salespersons course).\n- Pass the State real estate broker’s exam.\n\nA broker's license must be renewed every 2 years.\n\nAssociate broker\nAssociate real estate brokers must fulfill the same requirements as a broker (they must obtain their brokers license), but their status in the firm is the same as that of a salesperson.\n\nPocket Card\nThe Department of State issues a real estate license and a pocket card.\nThe salesperson’s license is held with their sponsoring broker.\nThe salesperson must carry their pocket card at all times when doing business and show it on demand.\n\nSuspension or Revocation of Sponsor's License\nIf a broker’s license is suspended or revoked, each real estate salesperson working under that broker shall also have their licenses suspended.\nIn this case, the State deems the salesperson’s license as a ‘discontinuance of association with the broker being suspended’.\n\nLicense Exemptions\n- Attorneys admitted to the NY State Bar are exempt from obtaining a license if they represent a client. If an attorney wants to employ salespersons, they then must obtain a broker’s license.\n- Public officers are exempt when performing official duties.\n- Persons under the judgment or order of a court.\n\nIt is important to note that if a licensed attorney wants to have salespersons working under them (the attorney acts as their sponsoring broker), the attorney must obtain a broker’s license.\n\nAdvertising\nAccording to section 175.25 of Article 12-A of the NY Real Property Law:\n\"All advertisements placed by a broker must indicate that the advertiser is a broker or give the name of the broker and his telephone number.\nAll advertisements placed by a broker which state that property is in the vicinity of a geographical area or territorial subdivision must indicate as part of such advertisement the name of the geographical area or territorial subdivision in which such property is actually located.”\n\nBlind Advertising\nAll ads by a licensee must indicate that the advertiser is a broker and give the name and telephone number of the broker.\nAds that do not contain this information are called blind ads.\nBlind ads are illegal in New York State.\n\nStigmatized Property Disclosure\nAccording to Article 443-a of the NY Real Property Law, sellers and seller agents do not have to disclose the following facts when selling or leasing residential property:\n1) Occupants who have AIDS or other illnesses not transmitted through occupancy.\n2) Properties that were a site of death due to natural causes, accidents, suicide, homicide, crime, and other reasons.\n\nRecord Keeping\nBrokers must maintain records of all transactions for at least 3 years.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-2", "title": "Chapter 2: Law of Agency", "body": "Chapter 2: Law of Agency\nTypes of Agency\n\nGeneral Agent\nSomeone authorized to transact every kind of business for the principal.\nExample: Property Manager\n\nSpecial Agent\nAn agent with limited authority to act on behalf of the principal, such as created by a listing.\nExample: Real Estate Agent / Real Estate Broker\n\nUniversal Agent\nA universal agent has complete authority over any activity of the principal.\nExample: Power of Attorney\n\nAgent / Client Relationships\nThe buyer and/or seller is known as the Principal or Client.\n\nThe broker is known as the Agent.\n\nThe salesperson is a Sub-agent of their broker.\n\nBuyer Agency / Buyer Brokerage\nBuyer agency occurs when a purchaser/renter hires a broker to represent them.\n\nThe purchaser/renter employs a broker to locate a property. In this relationship, the buyer is the principal and the broker is the agent.\n\nA Buyer Representation Form should be signed between the buyer and broker.\n\nFiduciary Duties\nThe real estate agent serves as a fiduciary to the client.\nA fiduciary relationship implies great confidence and trust.\nAs a fiduciary, the agent is in a position of great trust by the client.\n\nUse the acronym OLD CAR to remember the agent’s fiduciary duties to their client.\nObedience – Agent shall follow the legal instructions of their client.\n\nLoyalty – Agent shall work in the best interests of their client.\n\nDisclosure of Information (Full Disclosure) – Agent shall promptly communicate all information about the transaction to their client. This includes presenting all offers to the client.\n\nConfidentiality – Agent shall not reveal confidential information about the client to prospective buyers, without the express consent from the client. Such confidential information may harm the client.\n\nAccountability – (refers to financial accountability) the agent must account for and promptly remit all money or property entrusted to the agent.\n\nReasonable Care and Duty to Account – Agent shall possess the necessary skills and training to perform their requested services.\n\nAgency Disclosure Form\nThe Agency Disclosure Form is a written explanation, to be signed by a prospective buyer or seller of real estate, explaining to the client the role that the broker plays in the transaction.\nThis Agency Disclosure Form is known as the ‘New York State Disclosure Form for Buyer and Seller’.\n\nThe Agency Disclosure Form outlines the following:\n– The agent’s duties to the client.\n– Explains that an agent owes a fiduciary duty to the client.\n– Allows for advance consent to dual agency.\n\nThe Agency Disclosure Form is not required for the sale of vacant land.\n\nAccording to Section 443 of the NYS Real Property Law, licensees must present a written Agency Disclosure Form that details consumer choices about representation at the first substantive contact.\n\nIf a seller or buyer refuses to sign the Agency Disclosure Form, the agent should do the following:\n- Document the names and time, date, and reasons for refusal to sign the disclosure form.\n- Complete the declaration form stating the facts, have it acknowledged, and retain a copy for their records for at least 3 years.\n\nDual Agency\nDual agency occurs when a broker represents both the buyer and seller in a transaction.\n\nDual agency is permitted in New York State; however, advanced informed consent by BOTH parties is required.\n\nDual agency inherently puts the agents fiduciary duty of loyalty at risk.\n\nUndisclosed Dual Agency is illegal in New York State.\n\nInstead, the agent should notify both parties and have them sign the Agency Disclosure form, which states that the agent is acting as a dual agent. This is known as Advance Consent to Dual Agency.\n\nDual Agency with Designated Agents\nA broker may elect to have designated agents within his/her office to represent both sides in the transaction.\nIn this case, one designated agent will represent the seller and another designated agent will represent the buyer.\nThis helps reduce the broker’s risk of violating their fiduciary duties to the client.\n\nEstoppel\nAn agency by estoppel exists when a principal does not stop an individual from representing his or her interests, thus creating an agency relationship between the two.\n\nListing Contracts\nA listing contract is created between a seller and a broker (NOT a salesperson).\n\nThe listing agreement creates an express agency relationship.\n\nThe following listing contracts are the most used by brokers:\n\nExclusive Right to Sell Agreement:\nThis listing contract offers the most security to the broker. The seller must work exclusively with the broker to sell their property. The broker is entitled to a commission even if the seller finds a buyer themselves.\n\nExclusive Agency Agreement:\nThe seller must work exclusively with the broker to sell their property, BUT the seller does not have to pay the broker a commission if they find a buyer themselves.\n\nOpen Listing Contract:\nThe seller is allowed to work with any broker who brings them a buyer. Only the broker who brings a buyer is entitled to a commission. This is the riskiest type of listing contract for a broker.\nAn open listing contract is an example of a unilateral contract.\n\nNet Listing\nA net listing is not technically a listing agreement, but a method of establishing the listing broker’s commission as all money above a specified net amount to the seller.\n\nNet listings are illegal in New York.\n\nCommissions\nReal Estate Salespersons/Agents DO NOT collect money or commissions.\nAny commissions earned are paid to the salesperson’s broker, who in turn, pays the salesperson his/her portion of the commission.\n\nCommissions are determined between the client and broker and are always negotiable (there is no ‘standard’ commission rate).\n\nCommissions are typically calculated as a percentage of the sales price (not the listing price).\n\nA commission is technically earned when the agent finds a “ready, willing and able buyer” for the seller.\n\nSherman Anti-Trust Act\nThe Sherman Anti-Trust Act made the following actions illegal:\n1) Price fixing\n2) Group boycotts\n3) Market allocation\n4) Tie-in arrangements\n\nMisrepresentation\nMisrepresentation means making an intentionally false statement to induce someone to contract.\n\nProperty Condition Disclosure Statement\nThe Property Condition Disclosure Act requires the seller to submit to the buyer, a Property Condition Disclosure Statement, prior to signing the contract of sale.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-3", "title": "Chapter 3: Legal Issues", "body": "Chapter 3\n\nChapter 3.A: Legal Issues - Estates and Interests\nReal Property vs Personal Property\nReal property is the land and improvements, and all legal rights, powers, and privileges of real estate ownership. Real property includes the bundle of rights.\n\nEverything that is not real property is personal property.\n\nPersonal property is also known as chattel.\n\nFixtures\nA fixture is personal property that attaches permanently to the land or improvements and becomes part of the real property.\n\nTrade Fixtures\nTrade fixtures are items of personal property that a business operator installs in rented building space.\n\nUnlike a typical fixture, a trade fixture is considered personal property of the business owner. It is assumed the business owner will take the trade fixtures with them when moving out of the rented space.\n\nFee Simple\nFee simple absolute provides the most complete form of ownership.\n\nOwnership in Severalty\nWhen title to real estate is in the name of only one person or entity, it is an estate (ownership) in severalty.\n\nCo-ownership\n\nJoint tenancy:\nJoint tenancy is a form of co-ownership by two or more persons, each of whom has an undivided interest WITH the “right of survivorship”.\n\nTenancy in common:\nTenancy is common is a form of co-ownership by two or more persons, each of whom has an undivided interest, WITHOUT the “right of survivorship”.\n\nTenancy by the entirety:\nThis form of co-ownership is limited to married couples.\n\n4 Unities of Co-ownership\nThe 4 possible unities include:\n1) Time\n2) Title\n3) Interest\n4) Possession\n\nLife Estates\nA life estate is ownership, possession, and control of a property for someone’s lifetime.\n\nLeasehold Estates\nA leasehold estate is a non-freehold of limited duration, providing the right of possession and control but not title.\n\nWater Rights\nLittoral Rights = Lake\nLittoral rights apply to property bordering a stationary body of water.\nRiparian Rights = River (stream)\nRiparian rights belong to the owner of a property bordering a flowing body of water.\n\nSupply and Demand\nReal estate values are driven by the concept of supply and demand.\n\nChapter 3.B: Legal Issues - Liens and Easements\nEasement\nAn easement is the right to cross or otherwise use someone else’s property for a specified purpose.\nAn easement is a nonpossessory interest in land owned by another.\n\nThe common term for an easement is “right-of-way”.\n\nEasements “run with the land”.\n\nEasement in gross\nA right of use in the land of another without the requirement that the holder of the right own adjoining land.\n\nEasement by necessity:\nUsed when a property owner is landlocked and needs to cross an adjacent property to get access to their property.\n\nEasement by prescription:\nObtained by use of land without the owner’s permission for a legally prescribed length of time.\nIn New York, the use must be open and obvious, and must continue uninterrupted for 10 years.\n\nEasement by implication:\nThis type of easement arises by implication from the conduct of the parties.\n\nEncroachments\nAn encroachment is a building, part of a building, or obstruction which intrudes upon the property of another.\n\nLiens\nA lien is a claim or charge against the property of another.\n\nMechanic’s Lien:\nThis type of lien applies to individuals or companies who have “supplied labor or materials that improve a property”.\n\nA mechanic’s lien is a type of involuntary, specific lien.\n\nMortgage Lien:\nThis is the most common type of lien.\n\nA mortgage lien is another example of a voluntary, specific lien.\n\nTax Lien:\nWhen a taxpayer is delinquent in paying property taxes, a tax lien attaches against the property.\nA tax lien takes the highest priority among other liens (even higher than a mortgage lien).\n\nChapter 3.C: Legal Issues - Deeds\nDeeds\nA deed is also called an instrument of conveyance.\n\n- The Grantor is the Seller (conveys the deed).\n- The Grantee is the Buyer (receives the deed).\n\nEssential Elements of a Deed:\n- Must be in-writing (according to the Statute of Frauds).\n- Include a grantor.\n- Include a grantee.\n- Contain a granting clause.\n- Provide evidence of consideration.\n- Include a legal description of the property.\n- Include an habendum clause.\n- Include limitations and subject-to clause.\n- The signature of the grantor.\n- Acknowledgement/recording.\n- Delivery and acceptance.\n\nConveyance\nThe transfer of the title of land from one to another.\n\nLegal description\nThe deed must contain an adequate formal legal description.\n\nSurvey\nA survey is a drawing prepared by a licensed surveyor, which shows the exact dimensions of a property and any improvements located on the property.\n\nFull Covenant and Warranty Deed\nThe Full Covenant and Warranty deed contains the broadest form of guarantee of title of any type of deed and provides the greatest protection to the grantee.\n\nDeed Restrictions\nDeed restrictions are a form of encumbrance on real property.\n\nChapter 3.D: Legal Issues - Title Closing & Costs\nTitle\nTitle is a legal right to ownership of a property.\n\nChain of title\nChain of title refers to the sequence of historical transfers of title to a property.\n\nAbstract of title\nAn abstract of title is a condensed history of title.\n\nDeed\nA deed is an official legal document that's used to transfer ownership of a property.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-4", "title": "Chapter 4: The Contract of Sales and Leases", "body": "Chapter 4: The Contract of Sales and Leases\nContract Requirements\n– In New York State, an individual must be at least 18 years of age to enter into a contract.\n– Minors (less than 18 years old) CANNOT enter into a contract. The contract is voidable if signed by a minor.\n– In New York State, an individual must be mentally and emotionally capable to enter into a contract.\n\nSigning the Sales Contract\nGenerally, the purchaser signs the contract of sale first because the purchaser is the party making the offer.\n\nBi-lateral vs Uni-lateral Contracts\n\nA bi-lateral contract includes two parties.\nMost contracts in real estate are bi-lateral.\n\nA uni-lateral contract is an “open contract” where one party promises to pay another party if the other party performs a specific action.\nAn open listing contract is an example of a uni-lateral contract.\n\nDown payment\nThe down payment is the portion of a property’s purchase price that is paid in cash and is not part of the mortgage loan.\n\nThe down payment must be placed in a separate escrow account.\n\nEarnest money deposit\nA deposit that a buyer makes at the time of submitting an offer to demonstrate the true intent of the purchase; also referred to as a binder, good faith deposit, and escrow deposit.\n\nProration\nThe division of certain settlement costs between buyer and seller.\n\nDischarge of Contracts\nA contract may be discharged or terminated in the following ways:\n1) Agreement of the parties\n2) Full performance\n3) Impossibility of performance\n4) Operation of law\n\nNovation:\nThis is the act of either:\n1) replacing an obligation to perform with a new obligation; or\n2) adding an obligation to perform; or\n3) replacing a party to an agreement with a new party.\n\nContract Remedies\n1) Specific performance\n2) Compensatory damages\n3) Liquidated damages\n4) Reformation\n\nRight of first refusal\nThe right of first refusal may be added to a sales contract or a lease.\n\nLeases\n\nUse Provisions in a Lease\nThe ‘use provisions’ is a clause in a lease that requires a tenant reasonably use the space for its intended use.\n\nAssignment vs. Sub-Lease\nIn an assignment, the assignee is responsible for paying the rent directly to the landlord.\nIn a sublease, the original tenant is still responsible to the landlord for the lease payments under the lease contract.\n\nEviction\nEviction is a legal proceeding by a landlord to recover possession of real property.\n\nActual eviction:\nActual eviction occurs when the landlord removes the tenant from the property without aid or control of the court system.\nActual eviction is wrongful use of self-help.\n\nConstructive Eviction\nThis occurs when the tenant is prevented from the quiet enjoyment of the property.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-5", "title": "Chapter 5: Real Estate Finance", "body": "Chapter 5: Real Estate Finance\nMortgagor / Mortgagee\nMortgagor is the borrower (typically the person buying the house)\nMortgagee is the lender or bank who provides a loan to the borrower or homeowner.\n\nTypes of Loans\nFixed-Rate Mortgage / Fully Amortized Loan\nThis is the most common type of loan.\n\nStraight Loan (also known as a Term Loan)\nThis is an interest-only loan.\n\nAdjustable Rate Mortgage (ARM)\nIn this type of loan, the monthly payment fluctuates based on a standard index.\n\nBlanket Mortgage\nA blanket mortgage is a type of commercial mortgage in which two or more parcels of real estate are pledged as security for payment of the mortgage debt.\n\nPurchase Money Mortgage\nA purchase money mortgage is a type of seller financing in which a mortgage is given by the buyer to the seller to cover part of the purchase price.\n\nWraparound Mortgage\nA wraparound mortgage is another type of seller financing.\n\nSwing/Bridge Loan\nA type of short-term loan.\n\nGraduated Payment Mortgage (GPM)\nIn a graduated payment mortgage, the monthly payments are lower in the early years of the mortgage term, but increase at specific intervals.\n\nConstruction Mortgage\nA construction mortgage is a form of interim, or temporary, short-term financing for creating improvements or buildings on a property.\n\nNegative Amortization\nOccurs when the monthly payment is less than full interest and does not pay any principal.\n\nConventional vs. Government Loans\nConventional loans are loans issued by commercial lenders without any participation by an agency of the federal government.\n\nConventional loans with an loan-to-value ratio greater than 80% need to obtain private mortgage insurance (PMI).\n\nThe most common type of government loan is an FHA-insured loan.\nMortgage insurance premium (MIP) is paid upfront when obtaining an FHA-insured loan.\n\nReal Estate Settlement Procedures Act (RESPA)\nAlso known as Regulation X.\n\nTruth in Lending Act (TILA) / Regulation Z\nTILA requires four main disclosures:\n1) Annual percentage rate\n2) Finance charge\n3) Amount financed\n4) Total amount of money to be paid toward the mortgage in principal and interest payments\n\nLoan to Value Ratio (LTV)\nLTV compares the amount financed to the purchase price.\n\nPoints and Buydowns\n1 point equals 1% of the loan amount.\n\nUsury Laws\nUsury laws govern the amount of interest that can be charged on a loan.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-6", "title": "Chapter 6: Land Use Regulations", "body": "Chapter 6: Land Use Regulations\nZoning\nZoning determines the usage allowed for a building or subdivision.\nZoning also determines the ‘bulk’ of a house or building.\n\nZoning Board of Appeals\nThe Zoning Board of Appeals is a local appointed Board that has the power to review administrative rulings made by the Planning Board or another legislative body.\nIt is the interpreter of the zoning ordinance.\nThe Zoning Board of Appeals is also responsible for granting variances.\n\nNon-Conforming Use\nA non-conforming use is a preexisting use of a property that no longer complies with the current zoning regulations. The non-conforming use is “grandfathered” in.\n\nVariance\nVariance is the authorization to improve or develop a particular property in a manner not authorized by the local zoning code.\n\nThere are use variances and area variances.\n\nBuilding Codes\nThe primary purpose of building codes is to ensure a safe, properly functioning environment for the occupants.\n\nEscheat\nIf the deceased property owner does not have any heirs, the property reverts to the State. This is known as escheat.\n\nEminent Domain / Condemnation\nEminent domain is the right of the government to acquire private property for necessary public use. The property owner must receive fair compensation.\n\nCondemnation is the act of taking private property for public use.\n\nPercolation\nPercolation is the movement of water through soil.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-7", "title": "Chapter 7: Construction / Environmental Issues", "body": "Chapter 7: Construction / Environmental Issues\nBuilding Construction\n\nWood Framing\nPlatform framing is the most common type of framing used in residential construction.\n\nBalloon framing is an alternative to platform framing; however, it is considered illegal in New York State.\n\nBuilding Elements\n\nFooting\nA footing is a horizontal concrete member, set in the soil, which supports a building’s foundation wall.\n\nSill Plate\nThe sill plate is a horizontal wood member that sits on top of the house’s foundation.\n\nStuds\nStuds are vertical wood members used to construct walls.\n\nJoists\nJoists are horizontal beams or timbers that support a floor.\n\nRoof Components:\nEave – the lowest part of the roof that projects beyond the wall of the structure.\nSoffit – The area under the roof extension.\nFascia – The area of material facing the outer edge of the soffit.\n\nPitch\nAlso known as the slope.\n\nFlashing\nFlashing is added at joints/bends/corners on the exterior of a house, which prevents water from entering the house.\n\nSheathing\nSheathing refers to panels that span between wall studs and cover the exterior wall or interior walls.\n\nR-Value\nR-value is a measurement of the ability of insulation to slow the transfer of heat or cold.\n\nBTU Ratings\nBTU stands for British Thermal Unit.\nBTU is a measure of heat energy.\n\nSpecifications / Blueprints\nSpecifications – A document provided by Architects that describes the quality of construction.\nBlueprints – Architectural drawings that describe the layout and construction of a house. These drawings describe the quantities used in construction.\n\nFuse\nA device used in electrical systems to protect against excessive current.\n\nCircuit Breakers\nCircuit breakers perform a similar function but are more convenient and safer than fuses.\n\nEnvironmental Issues\nCFCs have been shown to lead to the depletion of the ozone layer.\n\nRadon\nRadon is a colorless, odorless gas that is emitted from soils, rocks and water as a result of radioactive decay.\n\nAsbestos\nAsbestos is a naturally occurring mineral fiber sometimes found in older homes.\n\nLead\nThe Residential Lead-Based Paint Hazard Reduction Act of 1992 sets forth the procedures in disclosing the presence of lead-based paint for sales of properties built before 1978.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-8", "title": "Chapter 8: Valuation Process and Pricing Properties", "body": "Chapter 8: Valuation Process and Pricing Properties\nAppraisals\nAn appraisal is an estimate of a property’s value by an appraiser who is usually presumed to be an expert in his/her work.\nAn appraisal is specific to a certain date in time.\n\nResidential properties are typically appraised using the sales comparison approach.\n\nComparative Market Analysis (CMA)\nA CMA is a property evaluation that determines property value by comparing other properties currently on the market, properties that have recently sold, and expired listings.\n\nA CMA is NOT an appraisal. Instead, it is an opinion of value.\nA CMA is typically prepared by a real estate agent.\n\nMarket Value\nMarket value is the most probable price that a property should bring if exposed for sale in the open market for a reasonable period of time, with both the buyer and seller aware of current market conditions, neither being under duress.\n\nMarket Price\nMarket price refers to the actual selling price of a property.\n\nDirect vs Indirect Costs\nDirect costs include the cost of labor and materials.\nIndirect costs include architectural and engineering fees, attorney fees, and financing costs.\n\nObsolescence\nFunctional Obsolescence can be an outdated design or floor plan.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-9", "title": "Chapter 9: Human Rights and Fair Housing", "body": "Chapter 9: Human Rights and Fair Housing\nCivil Rights Act of 1866\nThe Civil Rights Act of 1866 has no exemptions and contains the blanket statement that ‘citizens have the same rights to inherit, buy, sell, or lease real and personal property.\nThe Civil Rights Act of 1866 is primarily interpreted to prohibit racial discrimination.\n\nCivil Rights Act of 1968\nThe Fair Housing Act was included as part of the Civil Rights Act of 1968.\n\nThe initial protected classes under the Fair Housing Act included:\n- Race\n- Color\n- Religion\n- National origin\n\nThe Housing and Community Development Act of 1974 added sex as a protected class to the Fair Housing Act.\n\nThe 1988 Amendment to the Civil Rights Act added two new protected classes:\n– Persons with mental or physical disabilities\n– Familial status\n\nTypes of Discrimination\nBlockbusting\nThe practice of inducing homeowners in a particular neighborhood to sell their homes quickly, often at below market prices, by creating the fear that the entry of a minority group or groups into the neighborhood will cause a precipitous decline in property values.\n\nSteering:\nThe practice in which real estate brokers guide prospective home buyers towards (or away) from certain neighborhoods based on their race.\n\nRedlining\nThe refusal to lend money within a specific area for various reasons. This practice is illegal.\n\nTesters\nTesters are volunteers, employees of federal programs, and people from civil rights groups who visit real estate offices posing as prospective home buyers to see if race influences the information or services that the broker or salesperson offers.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-10", "title": "Chapter 10: Real Estate Mathematics", "body": "Chapter 10: Real Estate Mathematics\nAreas\n1 side x 1 side = area of a square\nwidth x depth = area of a rectangle\n½ base x height = area of a triangle\n\nAcres\n1 Acre = 43,560 square feet\n1 Hectare = 2.47 Acres\n\nDebt-to-Income Ratio\nThe percentage of a consumer’s monthly gross income that goes towards paying debts.\nFormula: Recurring Monthly Debt / Gross Monthly Income\n\nCommissions\nCommissions are typically calculated as a percentage of the sales price (not the listing price).\n\nCash on Cash Return\nCash on cash return (COC) is a percentage return on money invested in a property by an investor.\n\nThe formula to determine COC is:\nAnnual Cash Flow / Down Payment = Cash on Cash Return\n\nCalculating Interest\nYou may be asked to calculate the amount paid in monthly interest on a loan.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-11", "title": "Chapter 11: Municipal Agencies", "body": "Chapter 11: Municipal Agencies\nBuilding Department\nThe Building Department is responsible for enforcing the building code and issuing building/construction permits.\n\nArchitectural Review Boards\nOversees and upholds the quality and aesthetics of a neighborhood, town, or city.\n\nPlanning Board\nA local elected or appointed government board charged with recommending to the local town or city council the boundaries of the various zoning districts and appropriate regulations to be enforced therein.\n\nHistoric Preservation / Landmark Commissions\nEstablished to review proposed projects within historic districts for compliance with standards established for new development or alteration or improvement of historic buildings and landmarks.\n\nMunicipal Engineer’s Office\nThe Municipal Engineer performs the following basic functions:\n– Estimate the costs of paving, sewers and sidewalks, and other public works projects.\n– Supervise streets and other public works activities\n– Issue permits to private contractors for street openings and curb and gutter construction.\n– Assume responsibility for sewage, water supply, distribution systems.\n\nNYS Department of Health\nThe NYS Department of Health performs the following basic functions:\n– Drinking water safety.\n– Septic tank approval.\n– Certain wastewater treatment approval.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-12", "title": "Chapter 12: Property Insurance", "body": "Chapter 12: Property Insurance\nHomeowners Policies\nHO-1: Basic Policy - This is a basic policy that insures the home and its contents against perils, including fire, theft, or vandalism.\n\nHO-3: Special Form Policy – The most widely used and recommended homeowners policy.\n\nHO-4: Tenants or Cooperative Owners Policies – Commonly referred to as renters insurance.\n\nHO-6: Condominium Unit Owners Policies – Insure against damage to the contents of an apartment, cooperative, or condominium.\n\nUmbrella Policy\nInsurance policy that covers amounts above those covered under one or more other primary policies.\nAlso called excess insurance.\n\nFlood insurance\nFlood insurance is often not covered in a homeowner’s insurance plan. It may be purchased separately.\n\nThe Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) administers the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP).\n\nLiability Insurance\nLiability insurance is an example of a monoline policy.\n\nCommercial General Liability Insurance (CGL)\nCommercial general liability insurance is a basic business liability policy that covers four forms of injury.\n\nActual Cash Value vs Replacement Cost\nActual cash value means that the insured is reimbursed for the replacement cost minus the physical depreciation of the lost or damaged property.\n\nReplacement cost means that the insured is covered and reimbursed for the actual cost of replacing the damaged property.\n\nNew York Property Insurance Underwriting Association (NYPIUA)\nThe NYPIUA is a pool of all insurance companies writing fire insurance in New York.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-13", "title": "Chapter 13: Licensee Safety", "body": "Chapter 13 - Licensee Safety\nLiability Insurance\nReal estate agents must carry liability insurance.\n\nSecurity Cameras\nReal estate offices should be equipped with security cameras in order to record possible break-ins.\n\nLighting\nParking lots outside of real estate offices should have adequate lighting.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-14", "title": "Chapter 14: Taxes and Assessments", "body": "Chapter 14: Taxes and Assessments\nAssessed Value vs Market Value\nMarket value is the amount a property would sell under normal conditions.\n\nThe assessed value is a percentage of the market value. The assessed value is used to calculate property taxes.\n\nAd Valorem\nProperty is taxed on an ad valorem basis, that is, according to value.\n\nThe Role of the Assessor\nThe assessor is an elected or appointed local official who has the legal authority to independently estimate the value of real property in an assessing unit.\n\nProtesting Assessments\nProperty owners can protest the assessed value of their property.\nTheir grievances are heard by the Board of Assessment Review.\n\nThe burden of proof is on the property owner to prove the assessor incorrect.\n\nThe four grounds for review in New York are unequal assessment, excessive assessment, unlawful assessment, and misclassification.\n\nExempt Properties\nProperties owned by religious organizations and government-owned properties are exempt tax assessments.\n\nSpecial Assessments\nSpecial assessments are assessments made against a property to pay for a public improvement by which the assessed property is supposed to be especially benefit from.\n\nHomestead vs Non-Homestead Properties\nHomestead = Residential\nNon-homestead = Commercial", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-15", "title": "Chapter 15: Condominiums and Cooperatives", "body": "Chapter 15: Condominiums and Cooperatives\nCondominiums\nCondominiums are considered real property.\nFor that reason, condo owners receive a deed a closing.\n\nCooperatives\nCooperatives are NOT considered real property.\nThe owner of a co-op receives a proprietary lease at closing.\nA proprietary lease is considered personal property.\n\nCondop\nA condop is a building that includes condominium and cooperative ownership in the same structure.\n\nBoard of Directors\nThe Board of Directors manages a cooperative.\n\nHouse Rules\nRules in a cooperative that cover common issues including garbage disposal, maintenance, noise, pet restrictions, and conflict resolution.\n\nBy-laws\nThe by-laws are the owner’s rights and obligations for a condominium.\n\nBoard Package\nIf a prospective buyer is looking to purchase a unit in a cooperative, the Board of Directors will most likely want the buyer to submit a board package.\n\nRight of First Refusal\nCondominium contracts typically contain a ‘Right of First Refusal’ clause.\n\nOffering Plan\nThe developer of a new condominium or cooperative building must file an Offering Plan with the NY Attorney General’s office.\n\nCPS-1\nCPS-1 stands for Cooperative Policy Statement.\nIt is used by real estate developers to test the market before building a condominium or cooperative building.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-16", "title": "Chapter 16: Commercial & Investment Properties", "body": "Chapter 16: Commercial & Investment Properties\nTypes of Leases\n\nGross Lease\nIn a gross lease, the landlord pays all expenses.\n\nNet Lease\nIn a net lease, the tenant pays some or all of the expenses.\n\nPercentage Lease\nA lease of property in which the rent is based upon the percentage of the volume of sales made upon the leased premises.\n\nGround Lease\nA ground lease is a long-term lease of unimproved land, usually for construction purposes.\n\nLoft Lease\nA loft lease is for the rental of floor space this is not generally divided into rooms.\n\nGraduated Lease\nA graduated lease is a lease in which the rent changes from period to period over the lease term.\n\nEscalation Clause\nAn escalation clause allows landlords to raise rents during the term of the lease.\n\nUse Clause in a Commercial Lease\nA use clause defines how the tenant can and cannot use the space.\n\nRentable vs Usable Square Footage\nUsable square footage is the area contained within a building that is actually occupied by a commercial tenant.\nRentable square footage equals the entire space, including the usable square footage and the tenant’s pro rata share of the building’s common areas.\n\nThe difference between the rentable and usable area in a commercial space is known as the loss factor.\n\nPro Forma\nA pro forma is an accounting statement that forecasts income and expenses for a period of time.\n\nLeverage\nLeverage is the use of borrowed capital (mortgage) to increase the potential return of an investment.\n\nNet Operating Income (NOI)\nThe net operating income is equal to the gross income from a building minus operating expenses.\n\nCapitalization Rate\nThe formula for Capitalization Rate is:\nNet Operating Income / Value = Capitalization Rate\n\nLiquidity\nReal estate is considered an illiquid asset because it cannot quickly or easily be sold.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-17", "title": "Chapter 17: Income Tax in Real Estate Transactions", "body": "Chapter 17: Income Tax in Real Estate Transactions\nThree Classifications of Income\nActive income – Money earned through salaries or in a business in which the taxpayer actively participates.\n\nPassive income – Money earned from investing in a business venture or partnership.\n\nPortfolio income – Money earned from Interest, annuities, dividends, and royalties.\n\nTax shelters\nAny method of reducing taxable income resulting in a reduction of the payments to tax collecting entities.\n\nLike-Kind Exchanges\nA 1031 tax-deferred exchange allows an individual to defer capital gains taxes on real estate bought and sold for investment purposes.\n\nStraight-Line Depreciation\nResidential buildings and improvements are depreciable over 27.5 years using straight-line depreciation.\nCommercial buildings and improvements depreciate over 39 years using straight-line depreciation.\n\nAdjusted Basis\nAdjusted basis is the original cost or other basis plus certain additions and minus certain deductions such as depreciation and casualty losses.\n\nCapital Gain\nCapital gain is the profit realized from the sale of any capital investment including real estate.\n\nCapital Gain Tax Break\nHome sellers may be eligible to exclude up to $250,000 if single or up to $500,000 if married of the capital gain on the sale of the residence.\n\nPermitted Tax Deductions\nThese include:\n1) Property taxes\n2) Mortgage interest\n\nProperty Tax Exemptions\nCertain qualified individuals may be eligible for a partial exemption in their property taxes.\nThese include:\n– Veterans\n– Senior Citizens\n– Disabled\nThe STAR program allows qualified owner-occupied, primary residences to be exempt from school property taxes.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-18", "title": "Chapter 18: Mortgage Brokerages", "body": "Chapter 18: Mortgage Brokerages\nNYS Department of Financial Services\nThe NYS Department of Financial Services registers and licenses all companies and individuals who conduct mortgage related services in New York.\n- This includes mortgage broker licenses.\n\nDual Agency Disclosure under the Banking and New York Real Property Laws\nWhen a mortgage broker representing the buyer is also the real estate broker representing the seller in the same transaction, a dual agency is created.\n\nThe dual agency relationship must be disclosed at the first substantive contact between the mortgage broker and the prospective buyer.\n\nThe buyer/borrower and the seller must sign a Mortgage Broker Disclosure Form.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}, {"id": "note-19", "title": "Chapter 19: Property Management", "body": "Chapter 19: Property Management\nTypes of Maintenance\n\nCorrective Maintenance:\nA maintenance task performed to identify, isolate, and rectify a problem with a property so that the property can be restored to an acceptable condition.\n\nAn example of corrective maintenance would include fixing a leaky faucet.\n\nPreventative Maintenance:\nPreventative maintenance involves keeping property and equipment in a good state of repair so as to minimize the need for more costly repair work or replacement.\n\nAn example of preventative maintenance would include changing air filters in air conditioners and furnaces.\n\nManagement Agreement\nA management agreement is signed between the property owner and the property manager.\n\nThis contract creates an agency relationship in which the owner is the principal and the property manager is the agent for the purposes specified in the agreement.\n\nThe management agreement creates a general agency relationship between the owner and property manager.\n\nOperating Statement\nThe operating statement is used by property managers to project the net operating income for the property.\n\nStabilized Budget\nA stabilized budget is a forecast of income and expenses as may be reasonably projected over a short term, typically five years.\n\nCapital Reserve Budget\nMoney set aside by a property owner for long-term capital expenditures to a property.\n\nReal Estate License Requirements\nWhen a property manager works for only one owner, a real estate license is not required.\n\nHowever, when an individual (or company) serves as a property manager for more than one owner, at least a real estate salesperson license is required.", "folder": "Course Notes", "pinned": false}], "chapters": [{"id": "chapter-1", "title": "Chapter 1: License Law and Regulations", "cards": [{"id": "card-1-1", "q": "According to the course notes, which New York State agency is primarily responsible for issuing real estate licenses, issuing pocket cards, and handing down disciplinary action?", "a": "The Department of State is primarily responsible for issuing real estate licenses, pocket cards, and handing down disciplinary action.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-2", "q": "According to Article 12-A of the New York State Real Property Law, who shall prosecute criminal actions for violations of the Real Property Law?", "a": "The Attorney General shall prosecute criminal actions for violations of the Real Property Law.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-3", "q": "What is the highest court in New York State?", "a": "The New York Court of Appeals is the highest court in New York State.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-4", "q": "What is the maximum fine the New York Department of State may impose for violations of the Real Property Law?", "a": "The Department of State may impose a fine not to exceed $1,000.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-5", "q": "How old must a person be to obtain a New York real estate salesperson license?", "a": "A real estate salesperson must be at least 18 years old.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-6", "q": "How long is a New York real estate salesperson license valid?", "a": "A real estate salesperson's license is valid for 2 years.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-7", "q": "How many hours of Continuing Education must a salesperson complete before renewing a license?", "a": "Before renewing a license, the salesperson must complete 22.5-hours of Continuing Education.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-1-8", "q": "How long must brokers maintain records of all transactions?", "a": "Brokers must maintain records of all transactions for at least 3 years.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-2", "title": "Chapter 2: Law of Agency", "cards": [{"id": "card-2-1", "q": "What is a general agent according to the course notes?", "a": "Someone authorized to transact every kind of business for the principal.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-2", "q": "What is a special agent according to the course notes?", "a": "An agent with limited authority to act on behalf of the principal, such as created by a listing.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-3", "q": "What is a universal agent according to the course notes?", "a": "A universal agent has complete authority over any activity of the principal.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-4", "q": "In an agency relationship, who is known as the Principal or Client?", "a": "The buyer and/or seller is known as the Principal or Client.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-5", "q": "In an agency relationship, who is known as the Agent?", "a": "The broker is known as the Agent.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-6", "q": "What does the acronym OLD CAR represent in the agent’s fiduciary duties?", "a": "Obedience, Loyalty, Disclosure of Information, Confidentiality, Accountability, and Reasonable Care and Duty to Account.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-7", "q": "When must licensees present a written Agency Disclosure Form?", "a": "Licensees must present a written Agency Disclosure Form at the first substantive contact.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-8", "q": "When is dual agency permitted in New York State?", "a": "Dual agency is permitted in New York State; however, advanced informed consent by BOTH parties is required.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-9", "q": "Is undisclosed dual agency legal in New York State?", "a": "Undisclosed Dual Agency is illegal in New York State.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-2-10", "q": "Why does an Exclusive Right to Sell Agreement offer the most security to the broker?", "a": "The broker is entitled to a commission even if the seller finds a buyer themselves.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-3", "title": "Chapter 3: Legal Issues", "cards": [{"id": "card-3-1", "q": "What is real property according to the course notes?", "a": "Real property is the land and improvements, and all legal rights, powers, and privileges of real estate ownership.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-2", "q": "What is personal property also known as?", "a": "Personal property is also known as chattel.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-3", "q": "What is a fixture?", "a": "A fixture is personal property that attaches permanently to the land or improvements and becomes part of the real property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-4", "q": "What form of ownership provides the most complete form of ownership?", "a": "Fee simple absolute provides the most complete form of ownership.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-5", "q": "What is the difference between joint tenancy and tenancy in common?", "a": "Joint tenancy includes the right of survivorship, while tenancy in common does not include the right of survivorship.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-6", "q": "What is an easement?", "a": "An easement is the right to cross or otherwise use someone else’s property for a specified purpose.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-7", "q": "How long must an easement by prescription continue uninterrupted in New York?", "a": "In New York, the use must be open and obvious, and must continue uninterrupted for 10 years.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-8", "q": "What is an encroachment?", "a": "An encroachment is a building, part of a building, or obstruction which intrudes upon the property of another.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-9", "q": "What is a lien?", "a": "A lien is a claim or charge against the property of another.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-10", "q": "Which lien takes the highest priority among other liens?", "a": "A tax lien takes the highest priority among other liens, even higher than a mortgage lien.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-11", "q": "Who is the grantor in a deed?", "a": "The Grantor is the Seller and conveys the deed.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-12", "q": "Who is the grantee in a deed?", "a": "The Grantee is the Buyer and receives the deed.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-13", "q": "What is a deed also called?", "a": "A deed is also called an instrument of conveyance.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-14", "q": "What is chain of title?", "a": "Chain of title refers to the sequence of historical transfers of title to a property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-3-15", "q": "What is an abstract of title?", "a": "An abstract of title is a condensed history of title.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-4", "title": "Chapter 4: The Contract of Sales and Leases", "cards": [{"id": "card-4-1", "q": "How old must an individual be to enter into a contract in New York State?", "a": "In New York State, an individual must be at least 18 years of age to enter into a contract.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-2", "q": "What is the status of a contract signed by a minor?", "a": "The contract is voidable if signed by a minor.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-3", "q": "Who generally signs the contract of sale first?", "a": "Generally, the purchaser signs the contract of sale first because the purchaser is the party making the offer.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-4", "q": "Where must the down payment be placed?", "a": "The down payment must be placed in a separate escrow account.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-5", "q": "What is an earnest money deposit?", "a": "A deposit that a buyer makes at the time of submitting an offer to demonstrate the true intent of the purchase.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-6", "q": "What is proration?", "a": "Proration is the division of certain settlement costs between buyer and seller.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-7", "q": "What is novation?", "a": "Novation is replacing an obligation to perform with a new obligation, adding an obligation to perform, or replacing a party to an agreement with a new party.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-8", "q": "What is actual eviction?", "a": "Actual eviction occurs when the landlord removes the tenant from the property without aid or control of the court system.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-4-9", "q": "What is constructive eviction?", "a": "Constructive eviction occurs when the tenant is prevented from the quiet enjoyment of the property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-5", "title": "Chapter 5: Real Estate Finance", "cards": [{"id": "card-5-1", "q": "Who is the mortgagor in a mortgage transaction?", "a": "The mortgagor is the borrower, typically the person buying the house.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-2", "q": "Who is the mortgagee in a mortgage transaction?", "a": "The mortgagee is the lender or bank who provides a loan to the borrower or homeowner.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-3", "q": "What is a straight loan?", "a": "A straight loan is an interest-only loan.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-4", "q": "What is an adjustable rate mortgage?", "a": "In an adjustable rate mortgage, the monthly payment fluctuates based on a standard index.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-5", "q": "What is a blanket mortgage?", "a": "A blanket mortgage is a type of commercial mortgage in which two or more parcels of real estate are pledged as security for payment of the mortgage debt.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-6", "q": "When is private mortgage insurance required on a conventional loan?", "a": "Conventional loans with a loan-to-value ratio greater than 80% need to obtain private mortgage insurance.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-7", "q": "What is RESPA also known as?", "a": "The Real Estate Settlement Procedures Act is also known as Regulation X.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-8", "q": "What is TILA also known as?", "a": "The Truth in Lending Act is also known as Regulation Z.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-5-9", "q": "How much of the loan amount does one point equal?", "a": "One point equals 1% of the loan amount.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-6", "title": "Chapter 6: Land Use Regulations", "cards": [{"id": "card-6-1", "q": "What does zoning determine?", "a": "Zoning determines the usage allowed for a building or subdivision and the bulk of a house or building.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-2", "q": "What is a non-conforming use?", "a": "A non-conforming use is a preexisting use of a property that no longer complies with the current zoning regulations.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-3", "q": "What is a variance?", "a": "Variance is the authorization to improve or develop a particular property in a manner not authorized by the local zoning code.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-4", "q": "What is the primary purpose of building codes?", "a": "The primary purpose of building codes is to ensure a safe, properly functioning environment for the occupants.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-5", "q": "What is escheat?", "a": "If the deceased property owner does not have any heirs, the property reverts to the State. This is known as escheat.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-6", "q": "What is eminent domain?", "a": "Eminent domain is the right of the government to acquire private property for necessary public use.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-7", "q": "What is condemnation?", "a": "Condemnation is the act of taking private property for public use.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-6-8", "q": "What is percolation?", "a": "Percolation is the movement of water through soil.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-7", "title": "Chapter 7: Construction / Environmental Issues", "cards": [{"id": "card-7-1", "q": "What is the most common type of framing used in residential construction?", "a": "Platform framing is the most common type of framing used in residential construction.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-2", "q": "What is a footing?", "a": "A footing is a horizontal concrete member, set in the soil, which supports a building’s foundation wall.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-3", "q": "What is a sill plate?", "a": "The sill plate is a horizontal wood member that sits on top of the house’s foundation.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-4", "q": "What are studs?", "a": "Studs are vertical wood members used to construct walls.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-5", "q": "What are joists?", "a": "Joists are horizontal beams or timbers that support a floor.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-6", "q": "What is flashing used for?", "a": "Flashing is added at joints, bends, and corners on the exterior of a house, which prevents water from entering the house.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-7", "q": "What does R-value measure?", "a": "R-value is a measurement of the ability of insulation to slow the transfer of heat or cold.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-8", "q": "What does BTU stand for?", "a": "BTU stands for British Thermal Unit.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-9", "q": "What is radon?", "a": "Radon is a colorless, odorless gas that is emitted from soils, rocks and water as a result of radioactive decay.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-7-10", "q": "For properties built before what year must lead-based paint procedures be followed?", "a": "The Residential Lead-Based Paint Hazard Reduction Act of 1992 sets forth procedures for properties built before 1978.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-8", "title": "Chapter 8: Valuation Process and Pricing Properties", "cards": [{"id": "card-8-1", "q": "What is an appraisal?", "a": "An appraisal is an estimate of a property’s value by an appraiser who is usually presumed to be an expert in his or her work.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-2", "q": "Which appraisal approach is typically used for residential properties?", "a": "Residential properties are typically appraised using the sales comparison approach.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-3", "q": "What is a Comparative Market Analysis?", "a": "A CMA is a property evaluation that determines property value by comparing other properties currently on the market, properties that have recently sold, and expired listings.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-4", "q": "Is a CMA an appraisal?", "a": "A CMA is NOT an appraisal. Instead, it is an opinion of value.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-5", "q": "What is market value?", "a": "Market value is the most probable price that a property should bring if exposed for sale in the open market for a reasonable period of time.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-6", "q": "What is market price?", "a": "Market price refers to the actual selling price of a property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-7", "q": "What are direct costs?", "a": "Direct costs include the cost of labor and materials.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-8-8", "q": "What is functional obsolescence?", "a": "Functional Obsolescence can be an outdated design or floor plan.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-9", "title": "Chapter 9: Human Rights and Fair Housing", "cards": [{"id": "card-9-1", "q": "Does the Civil Rights Act of 1866 have any exemptions?", "a": "The Civil Rights Act of 1866 has no exemptions.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-2", "q": "What discrimination does the Civil Rights Act of 1866 primarily prohibit?", "a": "The Civil Rights Act of 1866 is primarily interpreted to prohibit racial discrimination.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-3", "q": "What were the initial protected classes under the Fair Housing Act?", "a": "The initial protected classes under the Fair Housing Act included race, color, religion, and national origin.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-4", "q": "What protected class was added in 1974?", "a": "The Housing and Community Development Act of 1974 added sex as a protected class.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-5", "q": "What protected classes were added in 1988?", "a": "The 1988 Amendment added persons with mental or physical disabilities and familial status.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-6", "q": "What is steering?", "a": "Steering is the practice in which real estate brokers guide prospective home buyers towards or away from certain neighborhoods based on their race.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-7", "q": "What is redlining?", "a": "Redlining is the refusal to lend money within a specific area for various reasons. This practice is illegal.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-9-8", "q": "What are testers?", "a": "Testers are people who visit real estate offices posing as prospective home buyers to see if race influences the information or services offered.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-10", "title": "Chapter 10: Real Estate Mathematics", "cards": [{"id": "card-10-1", "q": "What is the formula for the area of a square?", "a": "One side multiplied by one side equals the area of a square.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-2", "q": "What is the formula for the area of a rectangle?", "a": "Width multiplied by depth equals the area of a rectangle.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-3", "q": "What is the formula for the area of a triangle?", "a": "One-half base multiplied by height equals the area of a triangle.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-4", "q": "How many square feet are in one acre?", "a": "One acre equals 43,560 square feet.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-5", "q": "What is the debt-to-income ratio formula?", "a": "Recurring Monthly Debt divided by Gross Monthly Income.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-6", "q": "Commissions are typically calculated as a percentage of which price?", "a": "Commissions are typically calculated as a percentage of the sales price, not the listing price.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-10-7", "q": "What is the formula for cash-on-cash return?", "a": "Annual Cash Flow divided by Down Payment equals Cash on Cash Return.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-11", "title": "Chapter 11: Municipal Agencies", "cards": [{"id": "card-11-1", "q": "What is the Building Department responsible for?", "a": "The Building Department is responsible for enforcing the building code and issuing building and construction permits.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-11-2", "q": "What does the Architectural Review Board oversee?", "a": "The Architectural Review Board oversees and upholds the quality and aesthetics of a neighborhood, town, or city.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-11-3", "q": "What does the Planning Board prepare and amend?", "a": "The Planning Board prepares and amends a master plan for the community.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-11-4", "q": "What does the Historic Preservation or Landmark Commission review?", "a": "The commission reviews proposed projects within historic districts for compliance with established standards.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-11-5", "q": "What basic functions does the NYS Department of Health perform?", "a": "The NYS Department of Health performs drinking water safety, septic tank approval, and certain wastewater treatment approval.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-12", "title": "Chapter 12: Property Insurance", "cards": [{"id": "card-12-1", "q": "What is an HO-1 policy?", "a": "An HO-1 policy is a basic policy that insures the home and its contents against perils, including fire, theft, or vandalism.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-2", "q": "What is an HO-3 policy?", "a": "An HO-3 policy is the most widely used and recommended homeowners policy.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-3", "q": "What is an HO-4 policy?", "a": "An HO-4 policy is commonly referred to as renters insurance and also covers cooperative owners.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-4", "q": "What is an umbrella policy?", "a": "An umbrella policy covers amounts above those covered under one or more other primary policies.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-5", "q": "Who administers the National Flood Insurance Program?", "a": "The Federal Emergency Management Agency administers the National Flood Insurance Program.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-6", "q": "What is actual cash value?", "a": "Actual cash value means that the insured is reimbursed for the replacement cost minus the physical depreciation of the lost or damaged property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-12-7", "q": "What is replacement cost?", "a": "Replacement cost means that the insured is covered and reimbursed for the actual cost of replacing the damaged property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-13", "title": "Chapter 13: Licensee Safety", "cards": [{"id": "card-13-1", "q": "What type of insurance must real estate agents carry?", "a": "Real estate agents must carry liability insurance.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-13-2", "q": "Why should real estate offices be equipped with security cameras?", "a": "Real estate offices should be equipped with security cameras in order to record possible break-ins.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-13-3", "q": "What should parking lots outside of real estate offices have?", "a": "Parking lots outside of real estate offices should have adequate lighting.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-14", "title": "Chapter 14: Taxes and Assessments", "cards": [{"id": "card-14-1", "q": "What is market value?", "a": "Market value is the amount a property would sell under normal conditions.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-2", "q": "What is assessed value used for?", "a": "The assessed value is used to calculate property taxes.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-3", "q": "What does ad valorem mean?", "a": "Ad valorem means according to value.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-4", "q": "Who hears property tax assessment grievances?", "a": "Property owners’ grievances are heard by the Board of Assessment Review.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-5", "q": "Who has the burden of proof in an assessment protest?", "a": "The burden of proof is on the property owner to prove the assessor incorrect.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-6", "q": "What are the four grounds for review in New York?", "a": "The four grounds are unequal assessment, excessive assessment, unlawful assessment, and misclassification.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-7", "q": "What does homestead mean in the course notes?", "a": "Homestead means residential.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-14-8", "q": "What does non-homestead mean in the course notes?", "a": "Non-homestead means commercial.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-15", "title": "Chapter 15: Condominiums and Cooperatives", "cards": [{"id": "card-15-1", "q": "Are condominiums considered real property?", "a": "Condominiums are considered real property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-2", "q": "What does a condominium owner receive at closing?", "a": "A condominium owner receives a deed at closing.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-3", "q": "Are cooperatives considered real property?", "a": "Cooperatives are NOT considered real property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-4", "q": "What does a cooperative owner receive at closing?", "a": "The owner of a co-op receives a proprietary lease at closing.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-5", "q": "What is a condop?", "a": "A condop is a building that includes condominium and cooperative ownership in the same structure.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-6", "q": "Who manages a cooperative?", "a": "The Board of Directors manages a cooperative.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-7", "q": "What does a board package include?", "a": "The board package includes mostly financial documents.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-8", "q": "Where must an Offering Plan be filed?", "a": "The developer must file an Offering Plan with the New York Attorney General’s office.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-15-9", "q": "What does CPS-1 stand for?", "a": "CPS-1 stands for Cooperative Policy Statement.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-16", "title": "Chapter 16: Commercial & Investment Properties", "cards": [{"id": "card-16-1", "q": "In a gross lease, who pays all expenses?", "a": "In a gross lease, the landlord pays all expenses.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-2", "q": "In a net lease, who pays some or all expenses?", "a": "In a net lease, the tenant pays some or all of the expenses.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-3", "q": "What is a percentage lease?", "a": "A percentage lease is a lease in which the rent is based upon the percentage of the volume of sales made upon the leased premises.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-4", "q": "What is a ground lease?", "a": "A ground lease is a long-term lease of unimproved land, usually for construction purposes.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-5", "q": "What is a graduated lease?", "a": "A graduated lease is a lease in which the rent changes from period to period over the lease term.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-6", "q": "What is an escalation clause?", "a": "An escalation clause allows landlords to raise rents during the term of the lease.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-7", "q": "What is usable square footage?", "a": "Usable square footage is the area contained within a building that is actually occupied by a commercial tenant.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-8", "q": "What is rentable square footage?", "a": "Rentable square footage equals the entire space, including the usable square footage and the tenant’s pro rata share of the building’s common areas.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-9", "q": "What is net operating income?", "a": "The net operating income is equal to the gross income from a building minus operating expenses.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-10", "q": "What is the formula for capitalization rate?", "a": "Net Operating Income divided by Value equals Capitalization Rate.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-16-11", "q": "Why is real estate considered an illiquid asset?", "a": "Real estate is considered an illiquid asset because it cannot quickly or easily be sold.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-17", "title": "Chapter 17: Income Tax in Real Estate Transactions", "cards": [{"id": "card-17-1", "q": "What is active income?", "a": "Active income is money earned through salaries or in a business in which the taxpayer actively participates.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-2", "q": "What is passive income?", "a": "Passive income is money earned from investing in a business venture or partnership.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-3", "q": "What is portfolio income?", "a": "Portfolio income is money earned from interest, annuities, dividends, and royalties.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-4", "q": "What does a 1031 tax-deferred exchange allow?", "a": "A 1031 tax-deferred exchange allows an individual to defer capital gains taxes on real estate bought and sold for investment purposes.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-5", "q": "Over how many years are residential buildings and improvements depreciable?", "a": "Residential buildings and improvements are depreciable over 27.5 years using straight-line depreciation.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-6", "q": "Over how many years do commercial buildings and improvements depreciate?", "a": "Commercial buildings and improvements depreciate over 39 years using straight-line depreciation.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-7", "q": "What is adjusted basis?", "a": "Adjusted basis is the original cost or other basis plus certain additions and minus certain deductions such as depreciation and casualty losses.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-8", "q": "What is capital gain?", "a": "Capital gain is the profit realized from the sale of any capital investment including real estate.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-9", "q": "How much capital gain may a single home seller be eligible to exclude?", "a": "A single home seller may be eligible to exclude up to $250,000.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-17-10", "q": "How much capital gain may a married couple be eligible to exclude?", "a": "A married couple may be eligible to exclude up to $500,000.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-18", "title": "Chapter 18: Mortgage Brokerages", "cards": [{"id": "card-18-1", "q": "Which New York State agency registers and licenses companies and individuals who conduct mortgage-related services?", "a": "The NYS Department of Financial Services registers and licenses all companies and individuals who conduct mortgage related services in New York.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-18-2", "q": "When is a dual agency created under the Banking and New York Real Property Laws?", "a": "A dual agency is created when a mortgage broker representing the buyer is also the real estate broker representing the seller in the same transaction.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-18-3", "q": "When must the dual agency relationship be disclosed?", "a": "The dual agency relationship must be disclosed at the first substantive contact between the mortgage broker and the prospective buyer.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-18-4", "q": "What form must the buyer or borrower and the seller sign?", "a": "The buyer or borrower and the seller must sign a Mortgage Broker Disclosure Form.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}, {"id": "chapter-19", "title": "Chapter 19: Property Management", "cards": [{"id": "card-19-1", "q": "What is corrective maintenance?", "a": "Corrective maintenance is a maintenance task performed to identify, isolate, and rectify a problem with a property so that the property can be restored to an acceptable condition.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-2", "q": "What is an example of corrective maintenance?", "a": "An example of corrective maintenance would include fixing a leaky faucet.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-3", "q": "What is preventative maintenance?", "a": "Preventative maintenance involves keeping property and equipment in a good state of repair so as to minimize the need for more costly repair work or replacement.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-4", "q": "What is an example of preventative maintenance?", "a": "An example of preventative maintenance would include changing air filters in air conditioners and furnaces.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-5", "q": "Who signs a management agreement?", "a": "A management agreement is signed between the property owner and the property manager.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-6", "q": "What agency relationship does the management agreement create?", "a": "The management agreement creates a general agency relationship between the owner and property manager.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-7", "q": "What is the operating statement used to project?", "a": "The operating statement is used by property managers to project the net operating income for the property.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-8", "q": "What is a stabilized budget?", "a": "A stabilized budget is a forecast of income and expenses as may be reasonably projected over a short term, typically five years.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-9", "q": "When is a real estate license not required for a property manager?", "a": "When a property manager works for only one owner, a real estate license is not required.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}, {"id": "card-19-10", "q": "When is at least a real estate salesperson license required for property management?", "a": "When an individual or company serves as a property manager for more than one owner, at least a real estate salesperson license is required.", "known": false, "practice": false, "favorite": false}]}], "personalNotes": []};